**Fibonacci Sequence Using Recursion in C++**
=====================================================

The Fibonacci sequence is a series of numbers where a number is the addition of the last two numbers, starting with 0 and 1.

**Code**
--------

```cpp
#include <iostream>

/**
 * Function to calculate the nth Fibonacci number using recursion.
 * @param n The position of the Fibonacci number to calculate.
 * @return The nth Fibonacci number.
 */
int fibonacci(int n) {
    // Base cases: F(0) = 0 and F(1) = 1
    if (n == 0) {
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 1) {
        return 1;
    } 
    // Recursive case: F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)
    else {
        return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the position of the Fibonacci number: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    int result = fibonacci(n);
    std::cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << result << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

**How it Works**
----------------

1. The `fibonacci` function takes an integer `n` as input and calculates the `n`th Fibonacci number.
2. The base cases are when `n` is 0 or 1, in which case the function returns 0 or 1 respectively.
3. For any other value of `n`, the function calls itself with `n-1` and `n-2` to calculate the `n`th Fibonacci number by adding the `(n-1)`th and `(n-2)`th Fibonacci numbers.

**Note:** This recursive implementation has a high time complexity of O(2^n) due to repeated calculations, which can be optimized using memoization or dynamic programming.

**Sequence with Each Number Being the Sum of the Three Preceding Ones**
----------------------------------------------------------------

This sequence is known as the Tribonacci sequence. Here's a C++ program to find the nth Tribonacci number using recursion:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

/**
 * Function to calculate the nth Tribonacci number using recursion.
 * @param n The position of the Tribonacci number to calculate.
 * @return The nth Tribonacci number.
 */
int tribonacci(int n) {
    // Base cases: T(0) = 0, T(1) = -1, and T(2) = -1
    if (n == 0) {
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 1) {
        return -1;
    } else if (n == 2) {
        return -1;
    } 
    // Recursive case: T(n) = T(n-1) + T(n-2) + T(n-3)
    else {
        return tribonacci(n-1) + tribonacci(n-2) + tribonacci(n-3);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the position of the Tribonacci number: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    int result = tribonacci(n);
    std::cout << "The " << n << "th Tribonacci number is: " << result << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

**How it Works**
----------------

1. The `tribonacci` function takes an integer `n` as input and calculates the `n`th Tribonacci number.
2. The base cases are when `n` is 0, 1, or 2, in which case the function returns 0, -1, or -1 respectively.
3. For any other value of `n`, the function calls itself with `n-1`, `n-2`, and `n-3` to calculate the `n`th Tribonacci number by adding the `(n-1)`th, `(n-2)`th, and `(n-3)`th Tribonacci numbers.

**Note:** Similar to the Fibonacci sequence, this recursive implementation has a high time complexity of O(3^n) due to repeated calculations, which can be optimized using memoization or dynamic programming.

**Simple Joke Generator Website**

Here's a basic HTML, CSS, and JavaScript code to create a simple website that displays a random joke when a button is clicked.

### HTML (index.html)
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Joke Generator</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Joke Generator</h1>
    <button id="get-joke">Get a Joke!</button>
    <div id="joke-container">
        <p id="joke"></p>
    </div>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (style.css)
```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    text-align: center;
}

#joke-container {
    text-align: center;
    margin-top: 20px;
}

#joke {
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: bold;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}
```

### JavaScript (script.js)
```javascript
// List of jokes
const jokes = [
    "Why don't scientists trust atoms? Because they make up everything!",
    "Why don't eggs tell jokes? They'd crack each other up!",
    "Why did the tomato turn red? Because it saw the salad dressing!",
    "What do you call a fake noodle? An impasta!"
];

// Get a random joke from the list
function getRandomJoke() {
    const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length);
    return jokes[randomIndex];
}

// Display a random joke when the button is clicked
document.getElementById("get-joke").addEventListener("click", function () {
    const joke = getRandomJoke();
    document.getElementById("joke").innerHTML = joke;
});
```

**How it works:**

1. We define a list of jokes in the JavaScript code.
2. We create a function `getRandomJoke()` that returns a random joke from the list.
3. We add an event listener to the button that calls the `getRandomJoke()` function when clicked.
4. We update the innerHTML of the paragraph with the random joke.

**Save the HTML and JavaScript files in the same directory and open the HTML file in a web browser to see the joke generator in action!**

